article.description:
Alana Beard had 23 points and nine rebounds to
help the Washington Mystics lock up a playoff spot Friday night with a 74-67 victory over the Phoenix Mercury.
article.headline: Mystics win fifth game in a row
article.linkText: Mystical: Washington locks up playoff spot
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- At 12-16 and without All-Star Chamique Holdsclaw,
the Washington Mystics weren't thinking about the postseason.

"It's a dream come true," said Alana Beard, whose 23 points
and nine rebounds helped Washington and lock up a playoff spot
Friday night with a 74-67 victory over the Phoenix Mercury. "We
just buckled down on defense and have had the right people stepping
up at the right time."

Washington (17-16) has won five in a row and seven of 10 without
Holdsclaw, who ended her season on Sept. 8 because of an
undisclosed medical problem.

"We were destined to win," said Mystics coach Michael Adams.
"Our players just feel it."

Adams added, "Our players dedicated themselves and stepped up
since Chamique Holdsclaw (left)."

Diana Taurasi had 25 points for Phoenix, which lost its fourth
straight.

The Mercury (16-17) are on the brink of playoff elimination.
With the loss, they fell a half-game behind Sacramento for the
fourth and final postseason spot in the Western Conference. Phoenix
needs the Monarchs to lose their remaining two games -- both at home
against the Houston Comets and Minnesota Lynx -- and the Mercury
must beat Houston on Sunday.

The Monarchs would win a tiebreaker if both teams end up with
identical 17-17 records.

"We need three favors from everyone else to get in but the only
thing we can control is the game against Houston," said Taurasi.
"Ther is still something to be said about going .500 and improving
from last year. We can take that away from this."

Chasity Melvin added 15 points and 11 rebounds, her first
double-double of the season, for Washington, which clinched the
postseason berth with Charlotte's loss to San Antonio earlier
Friday.

"I told them at 12-16, if you want to get on the roller coaster
to get on because if you don't want to play then get out," said
Adams. "After that we started narrowing our rotation to eight or
nine players."

Washington went on a 14-2 run to take a 57-50 lead with 8:53
left. Phoenix never got closer then four the rest of the way.

"We are really working as a team," said Beard, the second
player taken in this year's draft behind Taurasi. "In the last two
weeks we have really come together and stepped up our games."

The Mystics held Phoenix, the WNBA's third-best 3-point shooting
team, to 5-of-19 from beyond the arc. The Mercury also missed seven
of 11 free throws. Washington also outrebounded Phoenix 36-29.

"We did a great job in the first half and it was pretty much
the same story of our season in a lot of ways," said Phoenix coach
Carrie Graf. "We couldn't string two halves together."

Despite missing seven of their first eight shots, the Mercury
scored the last eight points of the half to take a 39-28 lead at
halftime. Taurasi scored 17 points before the half.
